result.execSummary:
The defendant Ashley A Reed was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ashley A Reed in court, in custody, with attorney Samuel W. Benedict.   Jayne Davis Dewire appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant enters a guilty plea to Count 1.  Court finds defendant guilty.  Counts 2 and 3 dismissed and read in.  Cases 14CF839 and 14CM1413 dismissed and read in to this matter.

Court orders the following:
- Sentence withheld.  Credit for 68 days if revoked.
- 3 years Probation. 
- Court costs of $268.00; cash bail from 14CF839 to be applied.  Any remaining fine to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- DNA Surcharge of $250.00; cash bail from 14CF839 to be applied.  Any remaining surcharge to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- DNA Sample ordered
- Conditions of Probation:  Maintain absolute sobriety/Random UAs.  No use or possession of alcohol/drug paraphernalia/drugs without a valid prescription.  Valid prescriptions to be taken in the manner they were prescribed.  No contact with codefendant.  Maintain full-time employment and/or school after treatment is established.  DNA Sample if not yet provided, defendant to pay surcharge.
CONDITION TIME: 9 months - First 3 months STRAIGHT TIME.  Then remainder of condition time as NON WORKING HOURS WITH STANDARD RELEASE CONDITIONS.  Court would consider staying a portion of the condition time for Day Report Center after 4 months and upon written request of defendant.  

- Court grants expunction upon written request of the defendant and upon successful completion of Probation, payment of all costs/fees and no new criminal law violations.
